        <h3 class="short-notes-sub-heading">Use of Operators: Extracting Digits</h3>
        <p class="short-notes-paragraphs">
          <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Write a program that takes a four-digit integer from the user and shows the digits on the screen separately (e.g., if user enters `7531`, it displays `1, 3, 5, 7`).
        </p>
        <h4 class="short-notes-sub-heading">Solution Analysis:</h4>
        <ul class="short-notes-highlight-list">
          <li>Use the <strong>modulus operator (`%`) with 10</strong> to get the last digit (remainder). E.g., `1234 % 10` gives `4`.</li>
          <li>Use <strong>integer division (`/`) by 10</strong> to remove the last digit. E.g., `1234 / 10` gives `123`.</li>
          <li>Repeat this process to extract each digit. Reusing the same variable for the number after division (`number = number / 10;`) saves memory.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4 class="short-notes-sub-heading">Complete Program Example: Digit Extraction</h4>
        <div class="short-notes-code-block">
          <pre>
/* A program that takes a four digits integer from user and shows the digits on the
screen separately i.e. if user enters 7531, it displays 1,3,5,7 separately. */
#include &lt;iostream.h&gt;
main()
{
  // declare variables
  int number, digit;

  // prompt the user for input
  cout &lt;&lt; "Please enter 4-digit number:";
  cin &gt;&gt; number;

  // get the first digit and display it on screen
  digit = number % 10;
  cout &lt;&lt; "The digits are: ";
  cout &lt;&lt; digit &lt;&lt; ", ";

  // get the remaining three digits number
  number = number / 10;

  // get the next digit and display it
  digit = number % 10;
  cout &lt;&lt; digit &lt;&lt; ", ";

  // get the remaining two digits number
  number = number / 10;

  // get the next digit and display it
  digit = number % 10;
  cout &lt;&lt; digit &lt;&lt; ", ";

  // get the remaining one digit number
  number = number / 10;

  // get the next digit and display it
  digit = number % 10;
  cout &lt;&lt; digit;
}
          </pre>
        </div>
        <p class="short-notes-paragraphs">
          <strong>Sample Output:</strong>
          <br/>
          <code>Please enter 4-digit number: 5678</code>
          <br/>
          <code>The digits are: 8, 7, 6, 5</code>
        </p>

        <h3 class="short-notes-sub-heading">Use of Operators: Circle Calculations</h3>
        <p class="short-notes-paragraphs">
          <strong>Problem Statement:</strong> Write a program that takes the radius of a circle from the user and calculates the diameter, circumference, and area of the circle and displays the result.
        </p>
        <h4 class="short-notes-sub-heading">Solution Analysis:</h4>
        <ul class="short-notes-highlight-list">
          <li>Declare variables (`radius`, `diameter`, `circumference`, `area`) as `float` or `double` to handle decimal values.</li>
          <li>Prompt for and read `radius` using `cin`.</li>
          <li>Apply formulas:
            <ul class="short-notes-highlight-list nested-list">
              <li>Diameter = $2 	imes r$</li>
              <li>Circumference = $2 	imes \pi 	imes r$</li>
              <li>Area = $\pi 	imes r^2$</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Use `3.14` or `3.14159` for $\pi$. Ensure at least one operand in division is a decimal (`15.0 / 100`) to avoid integer truncation.</li>
          <li>Display results using `cout`.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4 class="short-notes-sub-heading">Complete Program Example: Circle Calculations</h4>
        <div class="short-notes-code-block">
          <pre>
/* Following program takes the radius of a circle from the user and calculates the
diameter, circumference and area of the circle and displays the result. */
#include &lt;iostream.h&gt;
main ()
{
  // declare variables
  float radius, diameter, circumference, area;

  // prompt the user for radius of a circle
  cout &lt;&lt; "Please enter the radius of the circle ";
  cin &gt;&gt; radius;

  // calculate the diameter, circumference and area of the circle
  // implementing formula i.e. diameter = 2 * r, circumference = 2 * PI * r and area = PI * r^2
  diameter = radius * 2;
  circumference = 2 * 3.14 * radius; // 3.14 is the value of PI
  area = 3.14 * radius * radius;

  // display the results
  cout &lt;&lt; "The diameter of the circle is : " &lt;&lt; diameter;
  cout &lt;&lt; "The circumference of the circle is : " &lt;&lt; circumference;
  cout &lt;&lt; "The area of the circle is : " &lt;&lt; area;
}
          </pre>
        </div>
        <p class="short-notes-paragraphs">
          <strong>Sample Output:</strong>
          <br/>
          <code>Please enter the radius of the circle 5</code>
          <br/>
          <code>The diameter of the circle is : 10</code>
          <br/>
          <code>The circumference of the circle is : 31.4</code>
          <br/>
          <code>The area of the circle is : 78.5</code>
        </p>

