        <h3 class="short-notes-sub-heading">Conditional Statements (Decision Making)</h3>
        <p class="short-notes-paragraphs">
          Decision making is a fundamental part of daily life and programming. It allows a program to execute different blocks of code based on whether a condition is true or false. In C++, the primary construct for decision making is the `if` statement.
        </p>
        <h4 class="short-notes-sub-heading"><code>if</code> Statement Structure:</h4>
        <div class="short-notes-code-block">
          <pre>
if ( condition )
  statement; // or a group of statements enclosed in {}
          </pre>
        </div>
        <ul class="short-notes-highlight-list">
          <li>If the `condition` inside the parentheses is `true`, the `statement` (or block of statements) immediately following the `if` is executed. Otherwise, it is skipped.</li>
          <li>A <strong>block of statements</strong> is enclosed in curly braces `{}`. It is good practice to always use braces, even for a single statement, to prevent logical errors and improve readability.</li>
          <li>Indentation improves readability but does not affect program logic. Semicolons are crucial to end statements.</li>
        </ul>

